@@eSepulchur Pasture -- Shrine of the First Claw Funerary Attestation@@N

The @@yShrine of the First Claw@@N maintains its own funerary protocols,
and they are @@rnon-negotiable@@N. When someone dies in Mafdet's
jurisdiction, their guardian-name is recorded, their effects cataloged
under Ledger House witness, and their remains handled according to
the @@yAttestation of Final Passage@@N: a sworn document naming the
dead, the cause, the witness, and the disposition of remains.

This is why Sepulchur Pasture horrifies us.

@@yMidgaard@@N solved its burial crisis with process -- then let the
process rot. Road dead routed to a field. Names copied from signet
rings @@ror witness testimony@@N -- sometimes guessed. Graves marked by
category, not certainty. The shepherd-priests' bell became a
@@rcivic machine@@N, and machines do not grieve. They @@rprocess@@N.

The @@d"deferred names"@@N appall us most. The dead entered into common
furrows @@rpending claim@@N, their rites withheld because no one paid
the @@yTithe of Last Burdens@@N. In Mafdet, a guardian-name persists
beyond death. You cannot defer a name. You cannot suspend an identity
pending payment. @@dA deferred name is a broken oath to someone who
can no longer protest.@@N

The quiet industry around grief -- clerks charging for corrections,
carriers misplacing evidence, wardens delaying remains, brokers
trading inheritance rumor -- is @@rpredatory attestation@@N at its most
obscene. In Mafdet, a Hazard Scribe who falsified a death attestation
would face the Shrine's justice -- swift and unsentimental.

The @@WViolet Compact's@@N quarantine doctrine turning the pasture into
a holding zone is familiar to our Quarantine Ledger. We classify
hazardous remains by tier. But we do not @@rtrap souls in legal
limbo@@N. Quarantine is containment with a timeline. Indefinite holding
without review is abandonment wearing process as a mask.

The @@rgravebell ringing twice@@N -- once from the tower, once from
beneath the furrows -- is what happens when the ledger fails the
dead. Names without bodies. Bodies without names. In Mafdet, the
Dual-Attestation Protocol requires two independent verifications.
@@yOne record cannot contradict another without triggering review.@@N

Midgaard's children whisper: @@d"Pay the living, name the dead, and
do not let the bell count twice."@@N

In Mafdet, we do not whisper it. We @@yswear@@N it at the Shrine, under
guardian-name, with witnesses. @@dThe bell rings once, and only once,
because someone is always counting.@@N
